{{refimprove|date=October 2012}} {{Infobox military conflict | conflict = Baren Township riot | partof = the [[Xinjiang conflict]] | image = Location of Akto within Xinjiang (China).png | image_size = 300px | caption = Location of Akto in Xinjiang | date = April 1990 | place = [[Akto County]], [[Xinjiang]] | territory = Chinese government regains control of Baren township | result = Uprising suppressed | combatant1 = [[File:The Flag of East Turkistan Republic.png|border|22px]] [[Turkistan Islamic Party]] | combatant2 = {{flagdeco|China}} [[People's Republic of China]] * {{armed forces|China}} * {{flagicon image|People's Armed Police Flag.svg|size=21px}} [[People's Armed Police]] | commander1 = [[Zeydin Yusup]]{{KIA}} | commander2 = [[Jiang Zeming]] | notes = | campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Xinjiang conflict}} }}
The '''Baren Township riot''' was an uprising and armed conflict that took place between [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] militants and [[Government of China|Chinese government]] forces in April 1990.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a523195.pdf|title=Approved for Public Release; Distribution is Unlimited The Uyghur Movement China’s Insurgency in Xinjiang|last=Patrick|first=MAJ Shawn M|publisher=School of Advanced Military Studies United States Army Command and General Staff College Fort Leavenworth, Kansas|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=27|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=DOCUMENT - CHINA: GROSS VIOLATIONS OF HUMAN RIGHTS IN THE XINJIANG UIGHUR AUTONOMOUS REGION (INCLUDES ERRATUM)|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/asa17/018/1999/en/|publisher=Amnesty International|access-date=31 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/27821503 VAN WIE DAVIS, ELIZABETH. "Uyghur Muslim Ethnic Separatism in Xinjiang, China". ''Asian Affairs'' 35, no. 1 (2008): 15-29.]</ref> It is unclear what happened during the armed conflict because reports of the incident vary greatly.<ref name=":0" />
== Chinese point of view == Chinese sources state that the uprising was initiated by 200 Uyghur militants armed with advanced weaponry who attacked Chinese [[paramilitary]] forces throughout the township of Baren.<ref name=":0" /> These reports indicate that [[Afghan]]i [[militia]] forces may have been directly involved. Reportedly, Afghan-trained Islamists set up loudspeakers in mosques of Baren Township urging the local Uyghur population to "rise up against Chinese oppression and work toward establishing an independent Uyghur Islamic state" while praising [[jihad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gUOnBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=baren+township+riot&source=bl&ots=3zdz9U-Arf&sig=Nvn-4CkZSOxLM5Pxd0B6Sp1tkzQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjRn82o8_nPAhVJqFQKHdm1Ddw4ChDoAQgoMAI#v=onepage&q=baren+township+riot&f=false|title=China's Spatial (Dis)integration: Political Economy of the Interethnic Unrest in Xinjiang|first=Rongxing|last=Guo|date=15 July 2015|publisher=Chandos Publishing|access-date=18 August 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref> In response, Chinese government forces crushed the uprising by force over the course of three days.<ref name=":0" />
== Uyghur point of view == On April 5, 1990, in [[Kizilsu]]'s [[Akto County]] and in the township of Baren, [[Zeydin Yusup]], the leader of the [[East Turkistan Islamic Party]],<ref name=":3">{{cite web|title=The 1990s: the turn towards repression|url=http://chinaperspectives.revues.org/648|publisher=chinaperspectives.revues.org|access-date=31 January 2013}}</ref> led a protest with around 200 men. They marched to the local government office and demanded an end to the mass immigration of [[Han Chinese|Han]] Chinese into [[Xinjiang]]. One source states that the protests were the result of 250 forced [[abortion]]s imposed upon local Uyghur women by the Chinese government.<ref name=":1" /> Another source states that the protests were the result of local Uyghurs not being allowed to build a mosque.<ref name=":2" />
The Chinese government initially sent in a detachment of armed police to the site of the disturbance.<ref name=":1" /> The Uyghur forces and the authorities started fighting, and the violence spread through the town.<ref name=":1" /> The uprising, which lasted for several days, ended when the Chinese government sent hundreds of heavily armed police and soldiers to quell the riots.<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/uighur-5.htm|title=Uighur Insurgency|first=John|last=Pike|date=|website=www.GlobalSecurity.org|access-date=18 August 2017}}</ref>
The [[Turkistan Islamic Party]] mentioned the Baren Township riot in issue 1 of its magazine, ''Islamic Turkistan'', in an article about the region's history.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=July 2008|title=ماذا تعرف عن تركستان الشرقية |url=https://archive.org/stream/IslamicTurkistan.mag1/islamiturkistan1#page/n19/mode/2up|magazine=تركستان الإسلامية|location=|publisher=|issue=العددالأول|page=١٨|access-date=}}</ref> The third issue of its magazine commemorated the death of Zeydin Yusup (Dia al din bin Yusuf), the TIP member involved in the Baren Township riot.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=June–July 2009|title=الشهيد ضياء الدين بن يوسف|url=https://azelin.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/e1b8a5izb-al-islc481mc4ab-al-turkistc481nc4abs-turkistan-islamic-party-22turkistc481n-al-islc481mc4abyyah-322.pdf|magazine=تركستان الإسلامية|location=|publisher=|issue=السنة الأولى العدد الرابع|pages=33–34|access-date=|author=عبد الله منصور}}</ref> Khalid Turkistani wrote an article in Issue 13 of the "Islamic Turkistan" magazine, saying he was a participant in the "jihad" in Baren and was jailed for it by the Chinese government in 1990.<ref>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |author=خالد تركستاني|date=June–July 2013|title= ذكريات من خلف القضبان ِ |url=https://azelin.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/e1b8a5izb-al-islc481mc4ab-al-turkistc481nc4ab_s-turkistan-islamic-party-e2809cturkistc481n-al-islc481mc4abyyah-13e280b3.pdf |magazine=تركستان الإسلامية |issue= العدد الثالث عشر|page=٥٣-٥٤ |location= |publisher= |access-date= }}</ref>
Doğu Türkistan Bülteni Haber Ajansı mentioned a brief history of the Turkistan Islamic Party, from Zeyiddin Yusuf founding it in 1988 in "East Turkestan", to its participation in the riots and insurgency, its "jihad in the path of Allah", its migration in 1996 under [[Hasan Mahsum]] to the Taliban controlled Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan, and its war since 2001 against the "Crusaders" for 15 years in the "Afghan jihad", to 2012, when it entered the Syrian Civil War.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date= 18 October 2016 |title= Türkistan İslam Cemati'nin Suriye'de ki Büyük Fetihleri – VİDEO HABER |url= http://www.doguturkistanbulteni.com/2016/10/18/turkistan-islam-cematinin-suriyede-ki-buyuk-fetihleri-video-haber/ |newspaper= Doğu Türkistan Bülteni Haber Ajansı |location= |access-date= }}</ref>
== Aftermath == One source states that the conflict ended on April 10, 1990, with 23 dead total and 21 injured, and that 232 Uyghur fighters were captured.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gUOnBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=baren+township+riot&source=bl&ots=3zdu5Z2Cnb&sig=ioTTltKwJ-keeJP07qi4JgFx660&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjJ5sLipN7OAhUWwGMKHQcWCnsQ6AEITDAH#v=onepage&q=baren%2520township%2520riot&f=false|title=China's Spatial (Dis)integration: Political Economy of the Interethnic Unrest in Xinjiang|last=Guo|first=Rongxing|date=15 July 2015|publisher=Chandos Publishing|isbn=9780081004036|language=en}}</ref> Another source states that as many as 1,600 people were killed during the armed conflict. In July 1990 the Chinese government in Xinjiang announced the arrest of 7,900 people citing the "criminal activities of ethnic splittists and other criminal offenders" as the reason.<ref name=":2">{{cite web|title=Uighur Developments in the 1990s|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/war/uighur-5.htm|publisher=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=31 January 2013}}</ref> An official account of civilian casualties is absent.{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}
