The '''Campaign to Stop Killer Robots''' is a group of [[non-governmental organizations]] who seek to pre-emptively ban [[lethal autonomous weapon]]s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merchant|first1=Brian|title=The Campaign to Stop Killer Robots Is Not Going Well|url=http://motherboard.vice.com/blog/the-campaign-to-stop-killer-robots-is-not-going-well|accessdate=14 April 2015|publisher=[[Vice (magazine)|VICE]]|date=22 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Horowitz|first1=Michael|last2=Scharre|first2=Paul|title=Do Killer Robots Save Lives?|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/11/killer-robots-save-lives-113010.html#.VSyy2pNcOjY|accessdate=14 April 2015|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Baum|first1=Seth|title=Stopping killer robots and other future threats|url=http://thebulletin.org/stopping-killer-robots-and-other-future-threats8012|accessdate=14 April 2015|publisher=[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]|date=22 February 2015}}</ref>
First launched in April 2013, member organizations joining the Campaign to Stop Killer Robots have urged governments and the [[United Nations]] to issue policy to outlaw the development of "lethal autonomous weapons systems" (LAWS).<ref>{{cite news|last1=McVeigh|first1=Tracey|title=Killer robots must be stopped, say campaigners|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/feb/23/stop-killer-robots|accessdate=14 April 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 February 2013}}</ref> The United Kingdom opposed such campaigns, with the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] declaring that "international humanitarian law already provides sufficient regulation for this area".<ref>{{Cite news|title = UK opposes international ban on developing 'killer robots'|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/13/uk-opposes-international-ban-on-developing-killer-robots|work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate = 28 July 2015|date=28 July 2015|first = Owen|last = Bowcott}}</ref>
In July 2015, over 1,000 experts in artificial intelligence signed a letter warning of the threat of an arms race in military artificial intelligence and calling for a ban on autonomous weapons. The letter was presented in [[Buenos Aires]] at the 24th [[International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence]] (IJCAI-15) and was co-signed by [[Stephen Hawking]], [[Elon Musk]], [[Steve Wozniak]], [[Noam Chomsky]], [[Skype]] co-founder [[Jaan Tallinn]] and [[Google DeepMind]] co-founder [[Demis Hassabis]], among others.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Musk, Wozniak and Hawking urge ban on warfare AI and autonomous weapons|url = https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jul/27/musk-wozniak-hawking-ban-ai-autonomous-weapons|work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate = 28 July 2015|date=27 July 2015|first = Samuel|last = Gibbs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Musk, Hawking Warn of Artificial Intelligence Weapons|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2015/07/27/musk-hawking-warn-of-artificial-intelligence-weapons/|work = [[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=28 July 2015|date=27 July 2015|first = Cat|last = Zakrzewski}}</ref>
