{{other uses}} '''Kinnikinnick''' is a [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] and [[First Nations]] [[herbalism|herbal]] [[smoking]] mixture, made from a traditional combination of leaves or barks. Recipes for the mixture vary, as do the uses, from social, to spiritual to medicinal.
==Etymology== The term "kinnikinnick" derives from the [[Lenape language|Unami Delaware]] {{IPA|/kələkːəˈnikːan/}}, "mixture" (''c.f.'' Ojibwe ''giniginige'' "to mix ''something animate'' with ''something inanimate''"),<ref>"''kiniginige''" in [[Frederic Baraga]] ''A Dictionary of the Ojibway Language''. Minnesota Historical Society Press (St. Paul, MN: 1992). {{ISBN|0-87351-281-2}}. Part II, page 189.</ref> from [[Proto-Algonquian language|Proto-Algonquian]] ''*kereken-'', "mix (it) with something different by hand".<ref>Flexner, Stuart Berg and Leonore Crary Hauck, eds.. ''The Random House Dictionary of the English Language'', 2nd ed. (unabridged). Random House (New York: 1987). Page 1058.</ref>
By extension, the name was also applied by the [[European colonization of the Americas|colonial European]] hunters, traders, and settlers to various shrubs of which the bark or leaves are used in the mixture,<ref name="HBAINMX">"Kinnikinnick" in [[Frederick Webb Hodge]] (editor) ''Handbook of American Indians North of Mexico''. Bureau of American Ethnology (Washington: 1911). Part 1, page 692.</ref> most often [[Bearberry]] (''Arctostaphylos spp.'')<ref name="Cutler"/> and to lesser degree, Red Osier Dogwood (''[[Cornus sericea]]'') and Silky Cornel (''[[Cornus amomum]]''), and even to Canadian Bunchberry (''[[Cornus canadensis]]''), Evergreen Sumac (''[[Rhus virens]]''), Littleleaf Sumac (''[[Rhus microphylla]]''), Smooth Sumac (''[[Rhus glabra]]''), and Staghorn Sumac (''[[Rhus typhina]]'').<ref>[http://www.cowasuck.org/lifestyle/pipes.cfm Smoking and Pipes], Cowasuck Band of the Pennacook-Abenaki People</ref>
==Indigenous names== * [[Algonquin language|Algonquin]]: ''nasemà'', "tobacco" (''mitàkozigan'', "unmixed tobacco"; ''apàkozigan'', "mixed tobacco") * [[Dakota language|Dakota]] and [[Lakota language|Lakota]]: ''čhaŋšáša'' * [[Menominee language|Menominee]] : ''ahpa͞esāwān'', "kinnikinnick" * [[Ottawa language|Odaawaa]]: ''semaa'', "tobacco" (''mtaaḳzigan'', "unmixed tobacco"; ''paaḳzigan'', "mixed tobacco") * [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]]: ''asemaa'', "tobacco" (''mitaakozigan'', "unmixed tobacco"; ''apaakozigan'', "mixed tobacco") * [[Shoshoni language|Shoshoni]]: ''äñ′-ka-kwi-nûp'', "kinnikinnick" <ref>{{cite paper |url=http://www.swsbm.com/Ethnobotany/Ethnobotan_of_Gosiute.pdf |title=The Ethno-botany of the Gosiute Indians of Utah |accessdate=2007-11-12 |last=Chamberlin |first=Ralph Vary |authorlink=Ralph Vary Chamberlin |date=1911 |work=Memoirs of the American Anthropological Association Vol II, part 5 |publisher= }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> * [[Winnebago language|Winnebago]]: ''roxį́šučkéra'', "bark to smoke" <ref>{{cite web |date=2005 |title=Hočąk Encyclopedia |url=http://www.hotcakencyclopedia.com/ho.Glossary.html#anchor12160902 |publisher=Richard L. Dieterle |accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>
==Preparation and use== The preparation varies by locality and [[First Nations|nation]]. [[John Russell Bartlett|Bartlett]] quotes [[James Hammond Trumbull|Trumbull]] as saying: "I have smoked half a dozen varieties of kinnikinnick in the North-west — all genuine; and have scraped and prepared the [[Cornus sericea|red willow]]-[[Bark (botany)|bark]], which is not much worse than [[Suffield, Connecticut|Suffield]] [[oak]]-leaf.<ref name="HBAINMX"/><ref name="DictAm">"[https://books.google.com/books?id=z5wYAAAAIAAJ&vq=Kinnikinick&pg=PA335#v=snippet&q=Kinnikinick&f=false "Kinnikinnick"] in John Russell Bartlett. ''Dictionary of Americanisms'', 4th Edition. Little, Brown, and Company (New York: 1877). Page 335.</ref>
Eastern tribes have traditionally used ''[[Nicotiana rustica]]'' for social smoking, while western tribes usually use a variety of kinnikinick for [[Ceremonial pipe|ceremonial use]].<ref name="Cutler">Charles L. Cutler. ''Tracks that speak: the legacy of Native American words in North American culture''. Houghton Mifflin Harcourt (Boston : 2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=CfekuKBLfpIC&lpg=PA174&ots=x3EkdlP9jc&dq=Kinnikinnick%20Ohio%20dogwood&pg=PA174#v=onepage&q=Kinnikinnick%20Ohio%20dogwood&f=false Pages 174–176.] {{ISBN|0-618-06510-5}}</ref> Cutler cites Edward S. Rutsch's study of the [[Iroquois]], listing ingredients used by other Native American tribes: leaves or bark of [[red osier dogwood]], [[arrowroot]], red [[sumac]], [[laurus nobilis|laurel]], [[ironwood]], [[Euonymus atropurpureus|wahoo]], [[squaw huckleberry]], [[Lobelia inflata|Indian tobacco]], [[cherry]] bark, and [[Verbascum|mullein]], among other ingredients.<ref name="Cutler"/>
==Historical references== Among the [[Ojibwe]], Densmore records the following: The material smoked by the Chippewa in earliest times were said to be the dried leaves of the bearberry (''Arctostaphylos uva-ursi'' (L.) Spreng.), and the dried, powdered root of a plant identified as [[Symphyotrichum novae-angliae|''Aster novae-angliae'' L.]]. Two sorts of bark were smoked, one being known as "red willow" ([[Cornus sericea|''Cornus stolonifera'' Michx.]]) and the other as "spotted willow" (''Cornus rugosa'' Lam.). The inner bark is used, after being toasted over a fire and powdered. It is then stored in a cloth or leather bag, and may be used on its own or in combination with other herbs.<ref>Frances Densmore. ''Chippewa Customs''. Bureau of American Ethnology (Washington: 1929) Reprint: Minnesota Historical Society Press (St. Paul: 1979). Pages 144-145.</ref>
{{cquote|The older hunter watched the singular preparations of his silent son, and suspecting that he had discovered signs of an enemy, arose, and saying he would go and cut a few sticks of the red willow [Kinnikinnick] to smoke, he left the lodge to go and see with his own and more experienced eyes, what were the signs of danger. |20px|20px| Warren, ''History of the Ojibway people''<ref>[[William W. Warren|Warren, William W.]]. ''History of the Ojibway People''. Minnesota Historical Society Press (St. Paul, MN : 1885; repr. 1984). Page 150 and page 411.</ref>}}
{{cquote|Tobacco used in the early day consisted of the inner bark of red dogwood — Indians on all reservations called it 'red willow.' An informant removed the outside bark of a twig with her thumbnail and noted that the remaining layer of bark when carefully shaven off served as tobacco, so-called kinnikinnick. Today kinnikinnick is a mixture of finely crushed inner bark of the red dogwood and shavings of plug tobacco. The mixture is worked with a mortar with pestle, both mortar and pestle being of wood. This mixture, too, is used today for ceremonial smoking. |20px|20px| Hilger, ''Chippewa Child Life''<ref>Inez Hilger. ''Chippewa Child Life and Its Cultural Background''. Minnesota Historical Society Press (St. Paul, MN : 1951, repr. 1992). Page 63.</ref>}}
{{cquote|'''Kinnikinic''', n. ''caŋṡaṡa''. |20px|20px| Williamson. ''An English-Dakota Dictionary''<ref>John P. Williamson. ''An English-Dakota Dictionary''. Minnesota Historical Society Press (St. Paul, MN : 1902; repr. 1992). [https://books.google.com/books?id=qnYCAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA95&ots=evnQqVzzG0&dq=cansasa%20dakota&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false Page 95.]</ref>}}
{{cquote| There are also certain creeks where the Indians resort to lay in a store of kinnik-kinnik (the inner bark of the red willow), which they use as a substitute for tobacco, and which has an aromatic and very pungent flavour. It is prepared for smoking by being scraped in thin curly flakes from the slender saplings, and crisped before the fire, after which it is rubbed between the hands into a form resembling leaf tobacco, and stored in skin bags for use. It has a highly narcotic effect on those not habituated to its use, and produces a heaviness sometimes approaching stupefaction, altogether different from the soothing effects of tobacco. |20px|20px|Ruxton, Geo. Frederick "Life in the Far West" 1848; quoted in "Mountain Men" edited by Rounds, Glen 1966, p.163<ref>Ruxton, Geo. Frederick "Life in the Far West" 1848; quoted in "Mountain Men" edited by Rounds, Glen 1966, p.163</ref>}}
